~Research on the Defense of the Mind~ In Jungian
psychology, similar to Freud, there is a concept
of the unconscious. As an example of unconscious
reactions, the ego, which forms consciousness,
tries to maintain personality in response to
psychological stressors.

There is a movement to exclude memories from the
unconscious realm. When emotions and reason
(consciousness) show contradictory reactions, in
other words, when contradictions arise,
unconscious reactions are shown, manifesting
symptoms such as amnesia.

Humans have a function to suppress intense
emotions and passions into the unconscious (the
function of the ego), which is a defense mechanism
to prevent the destruction of the mind caused by
psychological stress.
Actor03
\n<Detective>...? What kind of research were you conducting...?

~The Difference Between Ego and Self~ The ego is
the self that actively manipulates actions and
consciousness, using the five senses to perceive
the external world and recognize desires and
emotions within oneself.

The ego also has the role of storing experiences
and memories, and its biggest job is to maintain
personality and stability. (A function to defend
oneself)

The self is the totality of the mind and
encompasses the ego. It exists within the
unconscious, deeper than the sea and wider than
the universe. Therefore, it is something that
cannot be made conscious and has a function of
resisting when trying to unconsciously send
emotions in order to maintain the ego.

This is also considered to be due to the fact that
the self always has a tendency to strive for
higher levels.
Actor03

Functions 6~ As an example, I will mention
Hysterical Amnesia. When faced with anger towards
betrayal, one tends to make extreme choices,
driven by emotions.

However, conflicts arise between the consciousness
that tries to put the brakes on the responsibility
that arises from taking extreme actions. In such a
mental state, if one becomes unable to maintain
their personality due to contradictions caused by
conflicts,

The 'ego' is the memory that tries to suppress
and drive away the emotions of anger within the
unconscious, in order to maintain self-identity
and stability. This situation and its outcome are
what constitute Hysterical Amnesia.

~A Paper on the Existence of the Universal
Unconscious and Soul~ Research on what happens
after a person's death has been conducted since
ancient times, but the study of unobservable
phenomena has never been recognized as an academic
discipline.

However, based on the psychology of Jung and
Freud, several hypotheses were formulated, and as
a result of conducting research with subject X, it
was discovered that the key lies in the realm of
the universal unconscious.

If we assume that the existence of a soul is real,
where does it go after death? Perhaps the answer
lies in the collective unconscious, which everyone
shares but cannot accurately perceive.
